Nice analysis by @EPBResearch on market and claims outcomes following 3m10y inversions. Note I prefer continuing claims instead of initial claims as a recession indicator and see my recent commentary on both...

Another angle to look at this is how the 3m10y has moved relative to the onset of prior recessions.

We've already experienced the greatest inversion since the early 80s, and in fact, the current pace of the annual decline in the 3m10y inversion exceeds even the prior extreme inversion of the 80s.

A 3m10y inversion implies that the market believes the Fed is well into restrictive territory and will need to cut soon. There are also real economy implications from severe inversions (see recent banking squall). 

Parting words: the severity of the inversion does not have a good track record of predicting the severity of the subsequent recession. A slowdown is inarguably ahead, but an extreme 3m10y inversion doesn't mean a massive and deep recession must follow.

BREAKING: Germany Enters Recession

Germany's economy has entered a recession, according to official data released on Thursday. The country's gross domestic product (GDP) fell by 0.3% in the first quarter of 2023, following a 0.5% contraction in the fourth quarter of 2022.

The recession is being driven by a number of factors, including the war in Ukraine, rising energy prices, and supply chain disruptions. The war in Ukraine has led to a sharp increase in energy prices, which has had a knock-on effect on inflation. Inflation in Germany is currently at a record high of 7.9%, and is expected to remain elevated for the foreseeable future.

The war in Ukraine has also disrupted supply chains, which has made it more difficult for businesses to get the goods and services they need. This has led to production cuts and higher prices.

The recession is likely to have a significant impact on the German economy. Unemployment is expected to rise, and businesses are likely to cut investment and hiring. The recession is also likely to weigh on consumer spending, which is a major driver of the German economy.

The German government is taking steps to try to mitigate the impact of the recession. The government has announced a number of measures, including tax cuts and subsidies for businesses. However, it is unclear whether these measures will be enough to prevent the recession from deepening.

The recession in Germany is a sign of the challenges facing the global economy. The war in Ukraine, rising energy prices, and supply chain disruptions are all having a negative impact on economic growth. It is likely that the recession in Germany will be followed by recessions in other countries.
